SQL> -- ==========================================
SQL> -- 3. Condition Reorganisation Scenarios
SQL> -- ==========================================
SQL> 
SQL> -- Scenario 1: Reordering multiple Filters and Joins
SQL> --
SQL> -- Input Order:
SQL> -- 1. Join Condition
SQL> -- 2. Single Column Filter (on t2)
SQL> -- 3. Single Column Filter (on t1)
SQL> --
SQL> -- Expected Optimization:
SQL> -- Filters on t1 and t2 should be pushed up/evaluated before the join where possible,
SQL> -- or at least prioritized in the condition list if all are applied at the same level.
SQL> 
SQL> EXPLAIN SELECT t1.order_id, t2.region
  2 FROM t_opt_order t1, t_opt_customer t2
  3 WHERE t1.cust_id = t2.cust_id      -- Join
  4   AND t2.region = 'North'          -- Filter 1
  5   AND t1.status = 'COMPLETED';     -- Filter 2

EXPLAIN PLAN OUTPUT                                             
----------------------------------------------------------------
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
| Id | Operation               | Owner | Name              | Rows | Cost | StartCost | Bytes | Remark |
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
| 0  | SELECT STATEMENT        |       |                   | 1    | 2    | 2         |       |        |
| 1  |   MERGE JOIN            |       |                   | 1    | 2    | 2         |       |        |
| 2  |       TABLE ACCESS FULL | SYS   | T_OPT_ORDER T1    | 3    | 1    | 0         |       |        |
| 3  |       TABLE ACCESS FULL | SYS   | T_OPT_CUSTOMER T2 | 2    | 1    | 0         |       |        |
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Predicate Information (identified by id):                       
-----------------------------------------                       
    1 - access: T1.CUST_ID = T2.CUST_ID                         
    2 - filter: T1.STATUS = 'COMPLETED'                         
    3 - filter: T2.REGION = 'North'                             

13 rows fetched.

SQL> 
SQL> 
SQL> -- Scenario 2: Mixed Types with "False" Condition (if applicable)
SQL> -- Some optimizers prioritize conditions that evaluate to FALSE literals to short-circuit.
SQL> --
SQL> -- Input Order:
SQL> -- 1. Join
SQL> -- 2. Complex Expression
SQL> -- 3. 1=0 (False)
SQL> 
SQL> EXPLAIN SELECT *
  2 FROM t_opt_order t1, t_opt_customer t2
  3 WHERE t1.cust_id = t2.cust_id
  4   AND t1.amount * 2 > 100
  5   AND 1 = 0;

EXPLAIN PLAN OUTPUT                                             
----------------------------------------------------------------
---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
| Id | Operation                 | Owner | Name              | Rows | Cost | StartCost | Bytes | Remark |
---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
| 0  | SELECT STATEMENT          |       |                   | 10   | 6    | 0         |       |        |
| 1  |   ROWNUM COUNT            |       |                   | 10   | 6    | 0         |       |        |
| 2  |     NESTED LOOPS          |       |                   | 10   | 6    | 0         |       |        |
| 3  |         TABLE ACCESS FULL | SYS   | T_OPT_CUSTOMER T2 | 5    | 1    | 0         |       |        |
| 4  |         TABLE ACCESS FULL | SYS   | T_OPT_ORDER T1    | 6    | 1    | 0         |       |        |
---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Predicate Information (identified by id):                       
-----------------------------------------                       
    1 - filter: NULL IS NOT NULL                                
    2 - filter: NULL IS NOT NULL                                
    3 - filter: NULL IS NOT NULL                                
    4 - filter: NULL IS NOT NULL                                

15 rows fetched.

